{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534177"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:43:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:43:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14895"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14895"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.69,0.01,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59222"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7586"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14895"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44633"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"4440"},{"type":"tags","id":"4441"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"5808"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12030"},{"type":"tags","id":"12105"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43572"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59222"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset chest pain radiating to her back and shortness of breath at 32 weeks gestation. She has a family history of her mother dying suddenly during pregnancy at age 30. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. She works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. She has thin, translucent skin with visible veins. Her joints are hypermobile. Heart sounds are normal with no murmurs. The fetal heart rate is 160/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Marfan syndrome","Vascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome","Myocardial infarction","Amniotic fluid embolism","Pulmonary embolism"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of acute aortic dissection in pregnancy, with a concerning family history and physical examination findings pointing towards an inherited connective tissue disorder. The combination of thin translucent skin, hypermobile joints, and family history of sudden death in pregnancy strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Evascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (vEDS).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in any pregnant patient with acute chest pain and shortness of breath. However, the presence of hypermobile joints, thin skin, and family history make a genetic connective tissue disorder more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in pregnancy, particularly in the third trimester, but would not explain the physical features of a connective tissue disorder. The pattern of pain (radiating to back) is also more suggestive of aortic pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMarfan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with different physical features including tall stature, arachnodactyly, and lens dislocation. While it can cause aortic dissection in pregnancy, the skin findings and family history pattern are more consistent with vEDS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmniotic fluid embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden cardiovascular collapse, often accompanied by disseminated intravascular coagulation and acute respiratory distress. It would not explain the chronic features of a connective tissue disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome is an autosomal dominant condition caused by mutations in COL3A1, leading to defective type III collagen. Pregnancy significantly increases the risk of arterial rupture or dissection, with a maternal mortality rate of up to 25% during pregnancy. Urgent echocardiogram and vascular imaging are required, with consideration of immediate delivery if aortic dissection is confirmed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome carries significant maternal mortality risk due to arterial rupture during pregnancy.","Urgent echocardiogram is essential in pregnant patients with suspected aortic dissection.","Family history and examination for hypermobility are crucial in diagnosing inherited connective tissue disorders."],"references":["Chu J, Johnston TA, Geoghegan J, on behalf of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Maternal collapse in pregnancy and the puerperium: Green-top Guideline No. 56. BJOG 2019;126(12)","Haem T, Benson B, Dernoncourt A, Gondry J, Schmidt J, Foulon A. Vascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome and pregnancy: A systematic review. BJOG. 2024 Nov;131(12):1620-1629. doi: 10.1111/1471-0528.17893. Epub 2024 Jun 26. PMID: 38926786."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44633"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14895"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44633","link